WEBVTT

1
00:00:01.480 --> 00:00:04.920
Can you hear me? Good afternoon, everyone, and welcome to this session.

2
00:00:04.980 --> 00:00:08.860
My name is Jelani Zarif. I'm from Johns Hopkins University School of Medicine in

3
00:00:08.880 --> 00:00:10.800
the Sidney Kimmel Comprehensive Cancer Center.

4
00:00:12.160 --> 00:00:14.860
Hello, everyone. Thank you for coming. I'm Sonik Preethalik.

5
00:00:15.140 --> 00:00:19.130
I am a translational neuro-oncologist at West Virginia University,

6
00:00:19.340 --> 00:00:19.900
Morgantown.

7
00:00:21.340 --> 00:00:21.940
And we

8
00:00:22.900 --> 00:00:25.460
are excited to share this session.

9
00:00:26.160 --> 00:00:30.100
Our first talk will be from Jackson Weir from Harvard.

10
00:00:30.160 --> 00:00:30.380
He

11
00:00:31.220 --> 00:00:34.620
is a PhD candidate,

12
00:00:35.440 --> 00:00:39.200
and the title of his talk is "Bone Repair External State Program Drives

13
00:00:39.320 --> 00:00:42.960
Cancer Cell Dedifferentiation and Immune Invasion in Melanoma."

14
00:00:43.440 --> 00:00:44.520
Jackson, floor is yours.

15
00:00:44.860 --> 00:00:45.380
Thank you.

16
00:00:48.960 --> 00:00:50.860
Great. Hello, everyone. My name is Jackson.

17
00:00:51.340 --> 00:00:55.000
I'm a PhD candidate in Fay Chen's lab at the Broad, and I'm

18
00:00:55.040 --> 00:00:58.500
excited to talk about some spatial profiling that we've been doing over the last

19
00:00:58.560 --> 00:01:00.220
couple of years in melanoma.

20
00:01:01.540 --> 00:01:04.901
So for really five or 10 years now, we've been doing single-cell RNA

21
00:01:04.960 --> 00:01:08.500
sequencing on lots of tumors, and we've cataloged these

22
00:01:08.560 --> 00:01:12.540
transcriptional programs that are underlying the key cell types

23
00:01:12.760 --> 00:01:15.380
in tumors. And in parallel,

24
00:01:16.380 --> 00:01:20.200
maybe the last five years, spatial methods have enabled us to project

25
00:01:20.260 --> 00:01:23.780
these cell types from the tumors into their native tissue context and understand

26
00:01:23.800 --> 00:01:26.040
which cell types co-localize together.

27
00:01:26.560 --> 00:01:30.200
But really the Holy Grail is to understand the relationship between these two

28
00:01:30.240 --> 00:01:34.040
things, to understand how a cell's environment shapes its

29
00:01:34.050 --> 00:01:35.120
fine-grained cell state.

30
00:01:36.260 --> 00:01:39.920
And the way that we've been thinking about this in our lab is through this idea of

31
00:01:40.580 --> 00:01:44.480
a cell has both an internal state but also an external state.

32
00:01:44.800 --> 00:01:48.480
So in the same way that we define an internal state as a set of genes

33
00:01:48.800 --> 00:01:52.720
that co-vary across cells, we define an external state as a set

34
00:01:52.760 --> 00:01:56.420
of ligands that co-vary in a cell's neighborhood.

35
00:01:57.280 --> 00:02:01.090
And to really understand this link between internal states and cell neighborhoods,

36
00:02:01.380 --> 00:02:03.540
I think we've been technology limited

37
00:02:04.580 --> 00:02:06.780
by some of the spatial technologies that existed.

38
00:02:07.520 --> 00:02:10.461
So a couple of years ago, we developed this method called Slide-Tags, which is a

39
00:02:10.500 --> 00:02:13.940
method for truly single-cell spatial genomics.

40
00:02:14.220 --> 00:02:18.190
It works by we take a tissue section, and we melt it onto a bead array,

41
00:02:18.940 --> 00:02:20.100
where each bead has

42
00:02:21.360 --> 00:02:25.300
spatial barcodes, millions of spatial barcodes attached to the bead via

43
00:02:25.340 --> 00:02:29.140
this photoclavable linker. So we hit the tissue and the beads with UV light,

44
00:02:29.280 --> 00:02:32.300
and we release the spatial barcodes into the tissue.

45
00:02:32.320 --> 00:02:35.720
We then isolate the nuclei and then profile them with single cell, and we can read

46
00:02:35.780 --> 00:02:39.580
out the spatial positions of each cell and get truly single-cell spatial

47
00:02:39.620 --> 00:02:40.120
profiling.

48
00:02:41.680 --> 00:02:45.660
And in our initial paper, we used Slide-Tags to profile this one pilot melanoma

49
00:02:45.700 --> 00:02:49.560
sample. And we have TCR information for the T cells, as

50
00:02:49.620 --> 00:02:51.420
well as state information for all the cells.

51
00:02:51.670 --> 00:02:55.060
And what we find is that there's this one expanded CD8 T cell

52
00:02:55.100 --> 00:02:58.700
clonotype that differentially infiltrates into two

53
00:02:58.800 --> 00:03:02.560
lobes or two clones of the tumor. So we have this one

54
00:03:02.640 --> 00:03:05.140
lobe or clone that is more melanocytic.

55
00:03:05.470 --> 00:03:08.840
It's in this melanocytic-like state, and this is where all the CD8 T cells are

56
00:03:08.880 --> 00:03:12.870
infiltrating. But then there are very few CD8 T cells in this more mesenchymal

57
00:03:12.900 --> 00:03:13.560
region of the tumor.

58
00:03:14.390 --> 00:03:18.049
So we had three questions that we wondered, and we wanted to go about answering

59
00:03:18.080 --> 00:03:21.970
them in a more systematic way. So one, is which niches are supporting

60
00:03:22.000 --> 00:03:25.860
this T cell expansion? Two, which niches are excluding the CD8 T

61
00:03:25.880 --> 00:03:29.860
cells? And then finally, how are these niches interacting, and what's the crosstalk

62
00:03:29.880 --> 00:03:31.280
between niche and tumor?

63
00:03:32.720 --> 00:03:36.020
So working with Nir Hacohen's group and Moshe Sedgfeldman's group at the Broad and

64
00:03:36.040 --> 00:03:36.520
MGH,

65
00:03:37.400 --> 00:03:40.880
we collected this cohort of 30 Slide-Tags samples across

66
00:03:40.920 --> 00:03:44.860
metastatic human metastatic melanoma samples, across different metastatic sites

67
00:03:45.980 --> 00:03:47.980
with varying response to immune checkpoint blockade.

68
00:03:48.820 --> 00:03:52.300
And to start, we're going to forget about the tumor cells for a second and just

69
00:03:52.340 --> 00:03:54.760
focus on the immune and the stromal compartments.

70
00:03:55.440 --> 00:03:59.300
And we wanted to learn what the immune hub structure in melanoma looked like.

71
00:03:59.360 --> 00:04:01.220
So what we did is we took every

72
00:04:02.360 --> 00:04:06.260
pairwise combination of cell types, and we asked whether or not these cell

73
00:04:06.300 --> 00:04:07.329
types are enriched,

74
00:04:08.360 --> 00:04:11.600
spatially enriched or co-localized, or whether they're depleted in each

75
00:04:11.640 --> 00:04:15.590
other's neighborhood using this permutation testing framework.

76
00:04:15.620 --> 00:04:17.209
And I'm not going to talk about all the niches today,

77
00:04:18.880 --> 00:04:20.339
but I'm going to just highlight a couple.

78
00:04:20.399 --> 00:04:24.340
So first we find these stem immunity hubs that exist in melanoma that have been

79
00:04:24.360 --> 00:04:28.020
reported in other tumor types. So these are organized by these CCL19

80
00:04:28.040 --> 00:04:31.720
positive fibroblasts, and this is where most of the stem-like

81
00:04:31.740 --> 00:04:33.469
tumor-reactive CD8 T cells live.

82
00:04:34.950 --> 00:04:37.810
We find that the cycling tumor-reactive CD8s are found around

83
00:04:37.840 --> 00:04:41.430
CXCL10-positive macrophages. And then

84
00:04:41.480 --> 00:04:44.980
the tumor-reactive CD8s that lose their TCF7 expression, so they're no longer in

85
00:04:45.020 --> 00:04:48.820
this stem-like state, exist in what we call these immune effector hubs, which

86
00:04:48.900 --> 00:04:52.600
have lots of NK cells and these SIGLEC-10-positive macrophages that we think are

87
00:04:52.920 --> 00:04:54.100
efferocytosing the

88
00:04:54.940 --> 00:04:57.860
dying tumor cells that the immune effector cells are killing.

89
00:04:58.640 --> 00:05:01.940
But then we have this other hub, this fourth hub, that we call the

90
00:05:02.000 --> 00:05:05.280
anti-inflammatory hub, that has SPP1 macrophages, POSTN

91
00:05:05.340 --> 00:05:08.880
fibroblasts, and we don't really see a ton of T cells here.

92
00:05:08.900 --> 00:05:12.640
They're generally T cell excluded, but every once in a while, a T cell makes it

93
00:05:12.760 --> 00:05:14.040
into this anti-inflammatory hub.

94
00:05:14.390 --> 00:05:17.600
And we wanted to understand what's different about the T cells in these hubs versus

95
00:05:17.660 --> 00:05:19.740
the T cells in the other hubs in our samples.

96
00:05:21.000 --> 00:05:24.840
So first we looked at the internal state of the CD8 T cells, so what genes are just

97
00:05:24.880 --> 00:05:27.960
expressed in the T cells when they're in the hub versus not within the hub, and we

98
00:05:28.000 --> 00:05:31.460
find that the T cells in the anti-inflammatory hub have a more

99
00:05:31.480 --> 00:05:32.780
dysfunctional state.

100
00:05:34.580 --> 00:05:38.290
We can then look at the clonality of the T cells that are in immune

101
00:05:38.320 --> 00:05:41.820
effector hubs. In immune effector hubs, the CD8 T cells are generally, they belong

102
00:05:41.830 --> 00:05:45.580
to an expanded clonotype, but the T cells in the anti-inflammatory

103
00:05:45.620 --> 00:05:48.960
hubs belong to these singletons, so they're not expanded.

104
00:05:49.880 --> 00:05:53.720
And then finally, we can ask what the ligand environments around

105
00:05:53.780 --> 00:05:56.320
these T cells in the anti-inflammatory hub look like.

106
00:05:56.360 --> 00:06:00.300
In other words, what's the external state program that's being used

107
00:06:00.320 --> 00:06:02.160
by these anti-inflammatory hubs?

108
00:06:02.469 --> 00:06:06.450
And what we see are a bunch of tissue repair and wound-healing ligands,

109
00:06:06.820 --> 00:06:10.780
like SPP1, POSTN. There are some decoy receptors for cytokines, which

110
00:06:10.790 --> 00:06:14.576
are immune suppressiveSo it seems like this anti-inflammatory

111
00:06:14.916 --> 00:06:18.696
hub is activating this wound-healing response to

112
00:06:18.776 --> 00:06:21.976
suppress the immune response and maybe support the tumor.

113
00:06:22.916 --> 00:06:26.376
But then the question is, okay, so what's the relationship between these niches and

114
00:06:26.416 --> 00:06:27.116
the tumor state?

115
00:06:28.176 --> 00:06:31.796
So melanoma typically follows this dedifferentiation trajectory from this

116
00:06:31.856 --> 00:06:35.756
melanocytic-like state to this more neural crest

117
00:06:36.216 --> 00:06:39.666
state. It goes up its developmental hierarchy into, finally, this fully

118
00:06:39.716 --> 00:06:43.496
undifferentiated state. And we see all three of these states in our samples that we

119
00:06:43.516 --> 00:06:47.226
profiled. We also see some functional programs, like interferon-stimulated

120
00:06:47.316 --> 00:06:51.116
program, a cell cycle program. And if we look at the interferon-stimulated program

121
00:06:51.156 --> 00:06:54.376
for a second and we try to model the

122
00:06:54.436 --> 00:06:57.836
interferon program score in the cancer

123
00:06:57.856 --> 00:07:01.816
cells as a function of the density of each cell type

124
00:07:01.836 --> 00:07:02.576
in its neighborhood,

125
00:07:03.516 --> 00:07:07.276
we see that the immune effector hub cell types are

126
00:07:07.316 --> 00:07:11.236
predictive of interferon signaling in the tumor cells.

127
00:07:11.256 --> 00:07:14.736
So you can see here that these SIGLEC-10 macrophages co-localize really well with

128
00:07:15.196 --> 00:07:17.536
cancer cells that are expressing this interferon program.

129
00:07:18.596 --> 00:07:22.496
But then finally, we wanted to look at the neural crest cells, which are generally

130
00:07:22.516 --> 00:07:25.396
associated with poor response in patients.

131
00:07:26.176 --> 00:07:29.736
And what we see is that we identify a few different neural crest

132
00:07:29.876 --> 00:07:30.716
programs

133
00:07:31.816 --> 00:07:35.446
in our samples, and they really exist along this dedifferentiation

134
00:07:35.496 --> 00:07:39.056
trajectory from a more melanocytic-like state to a more

135
00:07:39.096 --> 00:07:42.376
undifferentiated, a more complete neural crest state.

136
00:07:42.706 --> 00:07:46.656
And what's cool is we can look at the spatial neighborhoods

137
00:07:46.736 --> 00:07:48.896
of cells along this trajectory.

138
00:07:49.836 --> 00:07:53.596
So tumor-reactive CD8s are in yellow, SPP1 Macs are in purple, and then postin

139
00:07:53.616 --> 00:07:57.506
fibroblasts are in green. And we see that along this trajectory

140
00:07:57.536 --> 00:08:01.056
from a more melanocytic-like state to neural crest-like state, we see early on

141
00:08:01.076 --> 00:08:05.016
there are lots of these CD8 T cells, but then eventually we see more

142
00:08:05.136 --> 00:08:08.716
SPP1 macrophages, more postin fibroblasts

143
00:08:09.176 --> 00:08:12.936
that are surrounding these more dedifferentiated cancer cells.

144
00:08:13.766 --> 00:08:17.616
And to formalize this, we can see that CD8s are down along this trajectory,

145
00:08:17.956 --> 00:08:21.075
while SPP1 Macs and postin fibroblasts are generally up.

146
00:08:22.116 --> 00:08:23.566
And then finally, at the niche level,

147
00:08:24.536 --> 00:08:28.396
if we model this trajectory score as a function of

148
00:08:28.956 --> 00:08:32.596
the niche cell types in these cancer cell neighborhoods, we see that this

149
00:08:32.606 --> 00:08:36.557
anti-inflammatory hub is the most predictive of a

150
00:08:36.636 --> 00:08:40.317
higher neural crest trajectory, so a less differentiated, more

151
00:08:40.356 --> 00:08:41.376
dedifferentiated tumor.

152
00:08:42.276 --> 00:08:45.206
And then finally, we wanted to take the ligands or a couple of these ligands from

153
00:08:45.236 --> 00:08:48.596
this tissue repair ligand program and put them on cancer cells and see what they're

154
00:08:48.616 --> 00:08:50.276
doing. We find that postin,

155
00:08:51.116 --> 00:08:54.476
which is this ECM ligand, when we put it on cancer cells, we see the cancer

156
00:08:54.516 --> 00:08:58.476
cells dedifferentiate from this melanocytic-like state into

157
00:08:58.516 --> 00:09:02.436
a more neural crest-y like state. And we put SPP1

158
00:09:02.496 --> 00:09:06.436
on cancer cells, specifically cancer cells in this neural crest state.

159
00:09:07.376 --> 00:09:11.196
We pre-treat with SPP1 and then later treat with interferon gamma, TNF alpha, and

160
00:09:11.236 --> 00:09:13.746
some other immune-killing cytokines.

161
00:09:14.276 --> 00:09:18.156
We see that SPP1 rescue is protecting cancer

162
00:09:18.176 --> 00:09:20.406
cells against immune cytokine killing.

163
00:09:21.326 --> 00:09:25.056
So to bring this all together, we see that tumor-reactive CD8 T cells in melanoma

164
00:09:25.066 --> 00:09:27.906
are found more in these stem immunity hubs and immune effector hubs and are

165
00:09:27.936 --> 00:09:30.416
generally excluded from the anti-inflammatory hubs.

166
00:09:31.196 --> 00:09:34.256
The T cells that do enter the anti-inflammatory hubs are more dysfunctional.

167
00:09:34.576 --> 00:09:38.016
They're less likely to be expanded, and they're surrounded by these tissue repair

168
00:09:38.056 --> 00:09:38.556
ligands.

169
00:09:39.386 --> 00:09:42.636
Immune effector hubs are predictive of interferon signaling, but anti-inflammatory

170
00:09:42.645 --> 00:09:45.506
hubs are kind of correlated with this dedifferentiation trajectory.

171
00:09:46.676 --> 00:09:50.336
And finally, we take some of these ligands from this tissue repair

172
00:09:50.476 --> 00:09:53.526
ligand program and find that they're supporting this

173
00:09:53.556 --> 00:09:57.286
dedifferentiation and immune evasion in

174
00:09:57.416 --> 00:09:59.956
melanoma. So yeah. Thank you very much.

175
00:10:00.356 --> 00:10:03.996
I'd like to thank Faye, Anir, Moshe, Alex, and the rest of the team

176
00:10:04.096 --> 00:10:06.395
for this project, and I'm happy to take any questions.

177
00:10:12.856 --> 00:10:14.796
If there are questions, you can go to the microphone.

178
00:10:21.336 --> 00:10:21.996
I'll start.

179
00:10:23.016 --> 00:10:25.236
Characterizing some of those T cells and those

180
00:10:25.456 --> 00:10:29.155
anti-inflammatory hubs, do you see any

181
00:10:29.196 --> 00:10:30.196
Tregs or?

182
00:10:30.436 --> 00:10:31.956
Yeah, that's a great question. So actually,

183
00:10:33.256 --> 00:10:36.756
the Treg... Okay, I think there's this ordering of which cell types

184
00:10:36.816 --> 00:10:40.276
arise in the anti-inflammatory hubs along the dedifferentiation trajectory.

185
00:10:40.396 --> 00:10:40.476
Yeah.

186
00:10:40.596 --> 00:10:44.396
We see that the postin fibroblasts come first, then the

187
00:10:44.456 --> 00:10:48.256
SPP1 macrophages, and then Tregs seem to come last, which is

188
00:10:48.316 --> 00:10:52.296
interesting. And Tregs we find are generally associated with a fully

189
00:10:52.336 --> 00:10:56.296
undifferentiated melanoma state, while kind of this anti-inflammatory hub

190
00:10:56.356 --> 00:10:59.796
is maybe more associated with the neural crest intermediate state.

191
00:11:00.536 --> 00:11:00.716
Yeah.

192
00:11:02.076 --> 00:11:06.056
Thank you. Great presentation. My question is, if you use

193
00:11:06.516 --> 00:11:07.836
immune checkpoint blockade-

194
00:11:08.016 --> 00:11:08.116
Mm.

195
00:11:08.636 --> 00:11:12.596
Would you see an improvement in dedifferentiation?

196
00:11:13.536 --> 00:11:13.736
Hmm.

197
00:11:14.596 --> 00:11:18.456
Oh, yeah. I guess usually there's this very interesting clinical phenomena,

198
00:11:19.716 --> 00:11:23.436
I understand, where usually if you have a tumor before checkpoint

199
00:11:23.476 --> 00:11:27.196
blockade, it's often more pigmented and kind of has its melanocytic

200
00:11:27.276 --> 00:11:31.216
identity. But clinicians often see by eye that patients that relapse

201
00:11:31.256 --> 00:11:34.596
or don't respond to immune checkpoint blockade, when they resect the

202
00:11:35.076 --> 00:11:38.966
tumor that's left after checkpoint, it no longer is in this pigmented state, which

203
00:11:38.996 --> 00:11:41.116
is a perfect marker for this dedifferentiation.

204
00:11:41.156 --> 00:11:44.836
So I think this is a very well-known clinical phenomena, and

205
00:11:44.856 --> 00:11:48.646
hopefully we're trying to provide the ligand programs that

206
00:11:48.716 --> 00:11:52.626
might be promoting this dedifferentiation that clinicians have seen for a very long

207
00:11:52.696 --> 00:11:52.896
time.

208
00:11:53.576 --> 00:11:54.096
Great work.

209
00:11:55.256 --> 00:11:55.676
Thank you.

210
00:12:00.116 --> 00:12:01.516
All right. Thank you so much, Jackson.

211
00:12:05.776 --> 00:12:09.336
Our next speaker is Matthew Ruane.

212
00:12:11.436 --> 00:12:12.636
He's a Charles S.

213
00:12:13.320 --> 00:12:17.240
Repsen Senior Fellow and Associate Research Scientist in the laboratory

214
00:12:17.320 --> 00:12:17.640
of Dr.

215
00:12:18.540 --> 00:12:22.320
Arpeyá in the Department of Microbiology and Immunology

216
00:12:22.460 --> 00:12:24.940
at Columbia University in New York.

217
00:12:25.600 --> 00:12:28.520
His talk is titled "Tumor-Specific Antibodies

218
00:12:29.040 --> 00:12:32.880
Elicited by Engineered Bacteria Promote Bladder

219
00:12:32.980 --> 00:12:35.480
Cancer Immunotherapy." The stage is yours.

220
00:12:36.700 --> 00:12:37.020
Thank you.

221
00:12:38.220 --> 00:12:41.320
Hi everyone. Thank you very much for coming today.

222
00:12:42.200 --> 00:12:45.700
So yeah, my name is Matthew Juan. I'm a surgeon scientist.

223
00:12:46.700 --> 00:12:50.630
I work at Columbia in Nick Arpeyá's lab, and our lab also

224
00:12:50.640 --> 00:12:52.560
collaborates with Tal Danino.

225
00:12:53.420 --> 00:12:55.880
Tal is a bioengineer at Columbia.

226
00:12:57.280 --> 00:13:00.899
And so we engineer bacteria for cancer therapy.

227
00:13:01.940 --> 00:13:05.560
So in this project, we asked a simple

228
00:13:05.660 --> 00:13:06.010
question,

229
00:13:07.340 --> 00:13:11.180
"Can we use bacteria to make bladder tumors

230
00:13:11.220 --> 00:13:14.260
more responsive to PD-1 blockade?"

231
00:13:17.460 --> 00:13:19.800
So bladder cancer is a common disease.

232
00:13:20.920 --> 00:13:24.700
Its incidence is rising. Most of the patients we

233
00:13:24.760 --> 00:13:28.320
see in the clinic have non-muscle invasive bladder cancer.

234
00:13:29.180 --> 00:13:30.800
And for those patients,

235
00:13:31.760 --> 00:13:35.640
we aim to preserve the bladder. Those patients have basically a pretty

236
00:13:35.740 --> 00:13:36.520
good prognosis.

237
00:13:37.820 --> 00:13:40.820
For the other group of patients with muscle invasive disease,

238
00:13:41.800 --> 00:13:45.580
the tumors are much more aggressive, and so the treatment is

239
00:13:45.640 --> 00:13:46.100
also

240
00:13:46.920 --> 00:13:47.660
more aggressive.

241
00:13:48.660 --> 00:13:51.760
So basically, that's how we treat these patients,

242
00:13:52.800 --> 00:13:56.760
how we used to treat, because now the field is rapidly

243
00:13:56.820 --> 00:14:00.560
evolving. But we used to treat these patients with a

244
00:14:00.580 --> 00:14:04.320
cisplatin-based chemo before a radical cystectomy.

245
00:14:04.900 --> 00:14:05.260
And,

246
00:14:06.240 --> 00:14:08.060
as you can see here, those patients

247
00:14:08.880 --> 00:14:12.120
still have a high risk of metastatic

248
00:14:12.440 --> 00:14:13.139
progression.

249
00:14:14.460 --> 00:14:15.760
So immunotherapy has been

250
00:14:16.600 --> 00:14:20.180
developed first in the metastatic setting, and rapidly it

251
00:14:20.320 --> 00:14:24.100
moved into the neoadjuvant space, so

252
00:14:24.139 --> 00:14:26.120
before radical cystectomy.

253
00:14:27.180 --> 00:14:30.520
And very recently, last November,

254
00:14:31.980 --> 00:14:35.920
immune checkpoint blockade, so PD-1 and PD-L1 blockade, have

255
00:14:35.960 --> 00:14:36.740
been approved

256
00:14:37.560 --> 00:14:40.680
in combination with antibody drug conjugates or

257
00:14:41.300 --> 00:14:45.220
chemotherapy before surgery and also after.

258
00:14:45.280 --> 00:14:47.880
It's like a perioperative treatment.

259
00:14:49.540 --> 00:14:53.140
But as a single agent, PD-1 and PD-L1

260
00:14:53.200 --> 00:14:57.140
blockade give about 25% of

261
00:14:57.340 --> 00:15:01.040
complete pathologic response. So there is a

262
00:15:01.080 --> 00:15:04.560
clear signal, there is a clear activity for these drugs

263
00:15:05.760 --> 00:15:08.020
in the neoadjuvant setting before surgery.

264
00:15:08.660 --> 00:15:12.440
But 25% is not enough, and so the idea here

265
00:15:12.560 --> 00:15:15.560
is to move that further.

266
00:15:16.940 --> 00:15:20.780
The idea is to use bacteria, basically, to prime the tumor,

267
00:15:20.960 --> 00:15:24.380
bladder tumors, before adding a PD-1 blockade to

268
00:15:24.480 --> 00:15:28.280
sensitize those bladder tumors to PD-1 blockade.

269
00:15:29.840 --> 00:15:30.460
So I'm going to

270
00:15:31.300 --> 00:15:33.140
show you how we tested that.

271
00:15:34.980 --> 00:15:36.920
So here you have two clinical trials.

272
00:15:38.080 --> 00:15:41.660
And so those patients have been treated with

273
00:15:41.880 --> 00:15:43.900
PD-1 blockade and PD-L1 blockade.

274
00:15:44.940 --> 00:15:47.140
And so keep an eye on the blue curve.

275
00:15:47.340 --> 00:15:49.100
You can see that patients with high

276
00:15:50.000 --> 00:15:53.800
levels of CXCL13 have better response to

277
00:15:54.700 --> 00:15:56.120
PD-1 and PD-L1 blockade.

278
00:15:58.100 --> 00:16:02.080
CXCL13 is linked to B cells, and also it's

279
00:16:02.180 --> 00:16:05.300
linked to lymphoid tissue development.

280
00:16:06.500 --> 00:16:10.200
And when you look at the tumors of these patients, there is a clear

281
00:16:10.280 --> 00:16:13.870
correlation between CXCL13 expression and the

282
00:16:13.920 --> 00:16:16.680
presence of tertiary lymphoid structures.

283
00:16:17.300 --> 00:16:20.840
So TLS are often described

284
00:16:21.480 --> 00:16:25.400
as ectopic lymph nodes, so they're aggregates of

285
00:16:25.440 --> 00:16:28.680
B cells and T cells. This one is particularly well

286
00:16:29.160 --> 00:16:33.010
defined and mature. You can see also in the center, a

287
00:16:34.020 --> 00:16:36.060
germinal center in this TLS.

288
00:16:38.020 --> 00:16:39.340
So the idea was to

289
00:16:41.080 --> 00:16:45.000
basically use the bacteria to deliver this chemokine in the

290
00:16:45.040 --> 00:16:47.200
bladder of those mice.

291
00:16:48.480 --> 00:16:51.060
And what has been shown also,

292
00:16:52.240 --> 00:16:56.020
25 years ago, is that CXCL13 alone is

293
00:16:56.080 --> 00:16:59.600
able to drive these tertiary lymphoid structures.

294
00:17:00.040 --> 00:17:03.740
So here it's a mouse model, an experimental mouse model, and the

295
00:17:03.800 --> 00:17:07.740
release of CXCL13 here in the pancreas of the

296
00:17:07.800 --> 00:17:11.580
mice is able to recruit both B cells and T

297
00:17:11.681 --> 00:17:15.580
cells. And you can see also this organization

298
00:17:15.641 --> 00:17:17.881
with a B cell zone and a T cell zone.

299
00:17:19.780 --> 00:17:23.560
CXCL13 is critical for B cell

300
00:17:23.600 --> 00:17:24.740
maturation and

301
00:17:25.921 --> 00:17:26.901
antibody production.

302
00:17:31.040 --> 00:17:34.200
So we had our therapeutic payload,

303
00:17:34.680 --> 00:17:38.200
CXCL13, but why did we choose

304
00:17:38.980 --> 00:17:42.340
E. coli Nissle to deliver basically this chemokine?

305
00:17:42.380 --> 00:17:45.600
And this idea comes from this clinical trial.

306
00:17:45.820 --> 00:17:48.800
So it's a clinical trial we had in France.

307
00:17:49.920 --> 00:17:53.060
Patients with bladder cancer received the

308
00:17:53.420 --> 00:17:56.000
pembrolizumab before treatment.

309
00:17:56.640 --> 00:17:56.980
And

310
00:17:58.180 --> 00:18:01.560
we observed that patients with a high level of

311
00:18:02.260 --> 00:18:06.240
anti-E. coli antibody, IgG antibodies in the blood before

312
00:18:06.300 --> 00:18:09.860
treatment, had a better response to PD-1

313
00:18:09.900 --> 00:18:13.400
blockade. Also, E. coli is the most frequent

314
00:18:13.820 --> 00:18:17.400
pathogens found in the urine, and we could also

315
00:18:17.440 --> 00:18:21.296
detect E. coli in bladder tumors.So it makes

316
00:18:21.306 --> 00:18:25.016
sense to use this bacteria as a

317
00:18:25.076 --> 00:18:26.356
system delivery approach.

318
00:18:31.296 --> 00:18:35.196
So that's where our collaboration with Tal Danino

319
00:18:35.936 --> 00:18:36.296
starts.

320
00:18:38.056 --> 00:18:41.316
We use this probiotic strain of E. coli.

321
00:18:41.356 --> 00:18:44.956
It's called the E. coli Nissle. So Nissle is

322
00:18:45.076 --> 00:18:48.956
a probiotic strain of E. coli. It's a non-pathogenic

323
00:18:49.056 --> 00:18:52.516
strain. You can find it and buy it actually online.

324
00:18:53.136 --> 00:18:54.436
It's commercially available.

325
00:18:55.616 --> 00:18:59.516
What makes our strain a little bit different is that we used this

326
00:19:00.116 --> 00:19:03.836
synchronized lysis circuit. So it's

327
00:19:03.916 --> 00:19:06.416
a quorum-sensing system.

328
00:19:07.896 --> 00:19:10.776
It's integrated into the genome of the bacteria.

329
00:19:11.506 --> 00:19:15.396
And so the way it works is that the bacteria

330
00:19:15.436 --> 00:19:18.496
can grow until they reach a critical number.

331
00:19:19.476 --> 00:19:21.076
A fraction of the bacteria lyse,

332
00:19:22.376 --> 00:19:26.356
and they release immunogenic bacterial compounds and

333
00:19:26.416 --> 00:19:30.116
also the therapeutic payload. But some bacteria remain

334
00:19:30.636 --> 00:19:32.876
alive, and so they can grow again,

335
00:19:33.796 --> 00:19:34.496
and release

336
00:19:35.996 --> 00:19:37.476
more payloads.

337
00:19:39.356 --> 00:19:43.196
So yeah, that's the schematic here to explain how it

338
00:19:43.236 --> 00:19:46.176
works. So the bacteria are injected here in the

339
00:19:46.216 --> 00:19:48.016
tumor. They grow.

340
00:19:48.936 --> 00:19:49.996
A fraction of the bacteria

341
00:19:51.536 --> 00:19:55.216
die and release their bacterial

342
00:19:55.296 --> 00:19:56.856
compounds and their therapeutic payload.

343
00:19:56.936 --> 00:20:00.296
Some bacteria can regrow because some of them remain alive.

344
00:20:00.646 --> 00:20:04.516
And also we can track them in vivo because

345
00:20:04.576 --> 00:20:05.216
we have this

346
00:20:06.356 --> 00:20:07.936
tracking system, imaging system.

347
00:20:12.536 --> 00:20:14.316
So we engineered this

348
00:20:15.536 --> 00:20:18.966
E. coli Nissle to produce the chemokine CXCL13.

349
00:20:20.636 --> 00:20:23.656
So we cloned the human chemokine and the mouse chemokine

350
00:20:24.616 --> 00:20:28.036
in the plasmid, and we transformed the bacteria with the

351
00:20:28.116 --> 00:20:31.376
plasmid that express those chemokines.

352
00:20:32.136 --> 00:20:35.716
And actually in vitro, we saw a better activity using

353
00:20:35.976 --> 00:20:39.056
mouse penisites. We saw a better activity with the human chemokine.

354
00:20:39.976 --> 00:20:40.316
So we

355
00:20:41.216 --> 00:20:42.796
moved forward with this

356
00:20:43.856 --> 00:20:44.436
chemokine.

357
00:20:45.576 --> 00:20:49.196
So the way we use it is that we deliver the

358
00:20:49.316 --> 00:20:52.976
bacteria into the bladder, in bladder tumor-bearing mice,

359
00:20:53.036 --> 00:20:56.896
also in orthotopic models. And so you can see here that

360
00:20:57.036 --> 00:20:59.316
the bacteria remain in the bladder.

361
00:20:59.416 --> 00:21:02.596
There is no spread to other organs.

362
00:21:05.936 --> 00:21:07.596
What we also found is that

363
00:21:08.456 --> 00:21:11.756
those bacteria specifically colonize bladder tumors.

364
00:21:12.356 --> 00:21:13.596
They do not colonize

365
00:21:15.176 --> 00:21:18.936
the normal tissue. So here we quantify the

366
00:21:18.996 --> 00:21:20.396
CFU in

367
00:21:22.616 --> 00:21:25.996
bladder tumor-free mice and bladder tumor-bearing mice, and you can see that you

368
00:21:26.156 --> 00:21:30.036
can detect bacteria only in bladder

369
00:21:30.076 --> 00:21:30.976
tumor-bearing mice.

370
00:21:33.496 --> 00:21:37.316
We also confirmed that the bacteria were able to release

371
00:21:37.356 --> 00:21:41.116
in vivo the chemokine by this

372
00:21:41.696 --> 00:21:42.756
ELISA assay.

373
00:21:47.556 --> 00:21:49.316
So next, we also tested

374
00:21:49.396 --> 00:21:53.216
the toxicity profile of this

375
00:21:53.256 --> 00:21:55.696
bacteria, and so we delivered the bacteria.

376
00:21:55.756 --> 00:21:59.676
So basically, the way we do is we insert a catheter

377
00:21:59.756 --> 00:22:02.876
into the bladder. It's a transurethral

378
00:22:02.936 --> 00:22:06.136
catheterization, and we deliver the bacteria into the bladder.

379
00:22:06.216 --> 00:22:09.656
So we repeated that four times, three days apart,

380
00:22:10.216 --> 00:22:12.536
and we monitored the body weight over time.

381
00:22:13.586 --> 00:22:17.276
There was no difference as compared to the PBS control group or the

382
00:22:17.336 --> 00:22:20.056
bacteria empty vector. That's the blue one.

383
00:22:21.916 --> 00:22:25.545
So basically, it says that this treatment is

384
00:22:25.796 --> 00:22:26.116
safe.

385
00:22:27.656 --> 00:22:29.736
And then we looked at the immune response.

386
00:22:30.676 --> 00:22:33.726
So here the mice were treated with three

387
00:22:33.776 --> 00:22:37.515
instillations of the engineered bacteria, the

388
00:22:37.576 --> 00:22:41.256
one with the empty vector, no production of CXCL13,

389
00:22:41.316 --> 00:22:44.686
BCG that we use for non-muscle invasive bladder cancer,

390
00:22:45.396 --> 00:22:49.276
and the PBS control. And so what you can appreciate here is that we

391
00:22:49.316 --> 00:22:52.296
saw this expansion of proliferative

392
00:22:52.836 --> 00:22:54.836
CD4 T helper cells

393
00:22:56.316 --> 00:22:57.786
upon exposure to this

394
00:22:59.596 --> 00:23:02.176
strain of Nissle expressing CXCL13.

395
00:23:04.116 --> 00:23:05.916
Those CD4 T cells were

396
00:23:08.396 --> 00:23:11.416
upregulating co-stimulatory

397
00:23:12.436 --> 00:23:14.396
receptor ICOS. They are also

398
00:23:16.016 --> 00:23:19.976
activated. They express a high level of the PD-1 receptor.

399
00:23:20.716 --> 00:23:22.176
So we thought it would be a good

400
00:23:23.836 --> 00:23:27.236
combination to use with the PD-1 blockade.

401
00:23:28.816 --> 00:23:32.656
So we combined basically this engineered bacteria with PD-1 blockade.

402
00:23:33.136 --> 00:23:36.656
And for that, we tested that in this very

403
00:23:36.676 --> 00:23:38.836
aggressive orthotopic model of bladder cancer.

404
00:23:39.296 --> 00:23:43.056
So that's the MB49 model. So the

405
00:23:43.076 --> 00:23:46.856
bladder cancer cells are instillated into the bladder, and we

406
00:23:46.956 --> 00:23:50.596
started the treatment at day 10, so you can appreciate

407
00:23:50.856 --> 00:23:53.656
the volume of the tumor in those mice.

408
00:23:54.676 --> 00:23:56.516
It's a very bulky tumor.

409
00:23:57.376 --> 00:23:59.336
And we combined that with PD-1 blockade

410
00:24:01.116 --> 00:24:03.616
as soon as the treatment with the bacteria started.

411
00:24:04.536 --> 00:24:06.996
And we saw a clear signal, a clear activity.

412
00:24:07.656 --> 00:24:11.456
50% of those mice are cured as compared to

413
00:24:11.476 --> 00:24:15.236
25% with PD-1 blockade alone. So we

414
00:24:15.296 --> 00:24:18.156
improved the survival of those mice by two

415
00:24:18.176 --> 00:24:22.862
times.And

416
00:24:22.912 --> 00:24:26.852
so we also re-challenged those mice by implanting

417
00:24:27.892 --> 00:24:28.272
the same

418
00:24:29.292 --> 00:24:33.272
MB49 cell lines on both lungs of

419
00:24:33.312 --> 00:24:36.232
those mice to test if they have a

420
00:24:37.232 --> 00:24:37.712
memory

421
00:24:39.192 --> 00:24:43.032
response. So you can see here that the

422
00:24:43.072 --> 00:24:46.552
mice here, that's the control group, and the mice

423
00:24:47.672 --> 00:24:49.632
who survived after the treatment.

424
00:24:50.572 --> 00:24:52.992
Basically, there was no tumor growth.

425
00:24:53.512 --> 00:24:55.612
The tumors did not grow back.

426
00:24:59.852 --> 00:25:03.412
Mechanistically, we also found that

427
00:25:03.932 --> 00:25:07.732
mice deficient with this subset of T cells, T follicular helper

428
00:25:07.752 --> 00:25:11.412
cells, basically did not respond to the treatment.

429
00:25:11.872 --> 00:25:15.852
So here it's a bone marrow chimera experiment, and mice

430
00:25:15.912 --> 00:25:17.752
lacking these CD4 helper

431
00:25:18.872 --> 00:25:20.562
T cells, T follicular helper cells,

432
00:25:21.832 --> 00:25:25.672
here, that's the group here. They do not respond to this treatment.

433
00:25:25.912 --> 00:25:29.592
So this suggests that those cells are critical to drive

434
00:25:29.892 --> 00:25:32.672
the therapeutic effects of this combination therapy.

435
00:25:35.372 --> 00:25:39.152
So our initial idea was to induce TLS, and so we looked at the

436
00:25:39.212 --> 00:25:42.692
bladder wall. So here it's a section of the bladder wall.

437
00:25:43.212 --> 00:25:46.912
The lumen is here. That's the urothelium,

438
00:25:47.932 --> 00:25:49.312
the lamina propria, and the muscle.

439
00:25:49.712 --> 00:25:53.692
So here it's an example of TLS with this aggregate of

440
00:25:53.912 --> 00:25:57.532
CD4 T cells and B cells. But they were very

441
00:25:57.652 --> 00:25:59.412
rare. We didn't find a lot.

442
00:26:00.612 --> 00:26:01.372
So

443
00:26:02.352 --> 00:26:06.342
the mechanism was not here, did not come from this

444
00:26:06.592 --> 00:26:07.612
induction of TLS.

445
00:26:09.092 --> 00:26:12.902
But then we looked at the draining lymph nodes, and there was a

446
00:26:12.952 --> 00:26:15.572
clear signal in the draining lymph nodes.

447
00:26:15.972 --> 00:26:19.672
So you can see here the mice received the bacteria plus the

448
00:26:19.692 --> 00:26:23.632
PD-1 blockade, and you see this expansion of germinal

449
00:26:23.672 --> 00:26:27.652
center B cells upon exposure to PD-1 blockade and

450
00:26:27.712 --> 00:26:29.032
our engineered bacteria.

451
00:26:30.892 --> 00:26:32.692
That's the quantification here.

452
00:26:33.692 --> 00:26:37.332
And also we found an increased number of plasma cells,

453
00:26:38.112 --> 00:26:41.752
suggesting that the B cells induced by this combination therapy

454
00:26:42.252 --> 00:26:45.332
led to the differentiation into

455
00:26:45.432 --> 00:26:46.852
antibody-secreting cells.

456
00:26:49.632 --> 00:26:53.432
And so finally we looked at the circulating

457
00:26:53.672 --> 00:26:57.172
antibodies. So we incubated the serum of those mice with

458
00:26:57.492 --> 00:27:00.432
MB49 cells in vitro, and we

459
00:27:00.812 --> 00:27:04.772
quantified the binding of IgG antibodies on the tumor

460
00:27:04.812 --> 00:27:05.072
cells.

461
00:27:05.752 --> 00:27:06.392
30 seconds.

462
00:27:08.032 --> 00:27:11.752
And so you see these increased levels of tumor-specific

463
00:27:11.952 --> 00:27:14.032
antibodies upon this combination therapy.

464
00:27:15.392 --> 00:27:18.532
So that's our working model. We engineered

465
00:27:18.572 --> 00:27:22.552
the probiotic strain of E. coli to make the

466
00:27:22.562 --> 00:27:24.172
human chemokine CXCL13.

467
00:27:25.252 --> 00:27:29.092
Upon intravesical delivery, those bacteria colonize bladder

468
00:27:29.152 --> 00:27:32.892
tumors. They also migrate to the lymph nodes and induce

469
00:27:32.912 --> 00:27:36.312
these germinal center responses with the production of

470
00:27:36.352 --> 00:27:38.092
tumor-specific antibodies.

471
00:27:38.932 --> 00:27:42.632
In the tumor, I didn't show that, but in the tumor, we saw also an

472
00:27:42.672 --> 00:27:46.412
increased activity of CD8 cytotoxic T cells.

473
00:27:47.672 --> 00:27:49.352
And with that, we cured

474
00:27:50.692 --> 00:27:54.132
50% of the mice, two times more than a PD-1 blockade alone.

475
00:27:55.672 --> 00:27:58.891
So thank you very much, and happy to take any questions.

476
00:28:03.692 --> 00:28:06.932
Thank you. We have time for one quick question. Excellent presentation.

