505
00:29:38.612 --> 00:29:42.312
So as many of you are probably aware, immunotherapy

506
00:29:42.452 --> 00:29:44.532
has been proved to be effective in

507
00:29:46.092 --> 00:29:48.612
treating multiple types of solid tumors.

508
00:29:49.052 --> 00:29:52.892
However, there are still patients who do not respond well

509
00:29:52.992 --> 00:29:55.532
and some who are experiencing relapse.

510
00:29:56.512 --> 00:29:57.392
Studies from

511
00:29:58.332 --> 00:30:02.012
tumors from responder and non-responder patients show the fact

512
00:30:02.052 --> 00:30:05.552
that a key determinant for predicting immunotherapy

513
00:30:05.692 --> 00:30:09.232
efficacy is the presence of CD8 positive T

514
00:30:09.332 --> 00:30:09.712
cells.

515
00:30:10.812 --> 00:30:14.252
Pan-cancer studies of immune transcriptional profiles

516
00:30:15.612 --> 00:30:18.942
also show that tumors having a low signature

517
00:30:19.132 --> 00:30:22.912
associated with trafficking of CD8 T cells into the tumors

518
00:30:23.532 --> 00:30:27.382
also had expression of genes associated with

519
00:30:27.412 --> 00:30:30.608
pro-tumor macrophages.Therefore,

520
00:30:30.618 --> 00:30:34.268
understanding how these suppressive populations

521
00:30:34.708 --> 00:30:37.868
affect the ability of CD8 T cells to infiltrate

522
00:30:37.948 --> 00:30:41.348
and function properly inside the tumors is

523
00:30:41.428 --> 00:30:45.268
necessary for expanding immunotherapy efficacy to a larger

524
00:30:45.308 --> 00:30:46.508
fraction of patients.

525
00:30:48.208 --> 00:30:51.968
Reprogramming anti-inflammatory tumor macrophages towards a

526
00:30:51.988 --> 00:30:55.838
pro-inflammatory phenotype has the potential to remodel the whole

527
00:30:55.928 --> 00:30:59.508
tumor microenvironment, leading to a more inflamed

528
00:30:59.568 --> 00:31:03.308
signature that would promote recruitment of more CD8 T cells

529
00:31:03.788 --> 00:31:07.388
and help maintain their function inside the tumor for longer.

530
00:31:08.308 --> 00:31:11.888
So maybe one way of reprogramming would be to target new

531
00:31:11.948 --> 00:31:15.288
molecules on myeloid cells that mediate immune suppression.

532
00:31:17.608 --> 00:31:21.508
So our lab has previously identified multiple molecules

533
00:31:21.608 --> 00:31:25.108
upregulated on dysfunctional cells isolated from

534
00:31:25.148 --> 00:31:28.888
melanoma mouse tumors, and GPNMB was one of

535
00:31:28.928 --> 00:31:32.288
them. Upon analysis of a human

536
00:31:32.668 --> 00:31:36.448
single-cell RNA sequencing breast cancer data set, we

537
00:31:36.608 --> 00:31:40.308
saw GPNMB as being upregulated on myeloid cells

538
00:31:40.408 --> 00:31:42.308
from non-responder patients.

539
00:31:43.288 --> 00:31:46.388
Out of all the immune cells from this data set, GPNMB

540
00:31:46.508 --> 00:31:50.388
was preferentially expressed in myeloid cells, and

541
00:31:50.688 --> 00:31:53.868
this was true among other data sets we

542
00:31:54.108 --> 00:31:54.748
analyzed.

543
00:31:55.828 --> 00:31:59.768
To further look into this in a mouse context, we started by

544
00:31:59.808 --> 00:32:02.848
looking at in vitro bone marrow-derived macrophages

545
00:32:03.348 --> 00:32:07.328
polarized towards a pro and anti-inflammatory phenotype and saw

546
00:32:07.388 --> 00:32:11.328
that GPNMB was upregulated on the anti-inflammatory

547
00:32:11.408 --> 00:32:11.988
subset.

548
00:32:13.408 --> 00:32:16.808
So what is GPNMB? It is a type I transmembrane

549
00:32:16.928 --> 00:32:20.328
glycoprotein. It can be cleaved by ADAM10

550
00:32:20.388 --> 00:32:24.028
protease and be shed as a soluble protein, and literature

551
00:32:24.088 --> 00:32:27.748
has proposed multiple receptors for it,

552
00:32:28.268 --> 00:32:30.768
different based on the disease context.

553
00:32:31.808 --> 00:32:35.768
So because we saw it as being upregulated on non-responder cancer

554
00:32:35.848 --> 00:32:39.708
patients, we wondered whether it has any involvement in

555
00:32:39.728 --> 00:32:43.408
tumor growth. And to do this, we generated full

556
00:32:43.468 --> 00:32:47.268
knockout GPNMB mice and looked at tumor

557
00:32:47.348 --> 00:32:49.428
growth in three different settings.

558
00:32:50.118 --> 00:32:54.028
We saw significant tumor control and increased survival in

559
00:32:54.088 --> 00:32:57.908
the B16-SIV subcutaneous model, in

560
00:32:58.028 --> 00:33:01.408
an orthotopic model of breast cancer,

561
00:33:01.988 --> 00:33:04.208
and in an experimental model of lung

562
00:33:04.268 --> 00:33:08.028
metastasis. Endpoint

563
00:33:08.148 --> 00:33:12.068
melanoma mouse tumors also had increased

564
00:33:12.228 --> 00:33:16.028
numbers of CD8 positive T cells in the knockout, as well

565
00:33:16.128 --> 00:33:19.188
as increased frequencies of memory

566
00:33:19.388 --> 00:33:22.718
activated, but also CD39 positive and

567
00:33:22.828 --> 00:33:26.088
TIM3 PD-1 double positive CD8 T cells.

568
00:33:26.908 --> 00:33:30.548
The myeloid compartment was also affected, showing increased

569
00:33:30.588 --> 00:33:34.128
numbers of the pro-inflammatory macrophages and

570
00:33:34.308 --> 00:33:35.128
monocytes.

571
00:33:36.388 --> 00:33:40.168
So we wanted to further investigate which cell

572
00:33:40.188 --> 00:33:43.808
types are affected the most by this GPNMB

573
00:33:43.868 --> 00:33:46.988
knockout, and for this, we performed single-cell RNA

574
00:33:47.108 --> 00:33:50.888
sequencing on the immune compartment and saw that the

575
00:33:50.948 --> 00:33:54.848
most affected cell types were the macrophages, followed by the

576
00:33:54.888 --> 00:33:55.528
T cells.

577
00:33:57.268 --> 00:34:00.728
After further analyzing the macrophage compartment, we

578
00:34:00.788 --> 00:34:04.428
identified eight different subsets, two of which

579
00:34:04.488 --> 00:34:08.348
were significantly different in terms of proportions between the wild

580
00:34:08.428 --> 00:34:11.708
type and the knockout. One subtype expressing

581
00:34:11.788 --> 00:34:15.508
CXCL10 gene and other pro-inflammatory genes was

582
00:34:15.888 --> 00:34:19.788
expanded in the knockout, while another one expressing mitochondrial

583
00:34:19.828 --> 00:34:23.089
genes, which are known to be associated with

584
00:34:23.908 --> 00:34:27.609
oxidative phosphorylation, was expanded in the wild type.

585
00:34:29.028 --> 00:34:32.879
Even though GPNMB is only expressed by

586
00:34:32.988 --> 00:34:36.908
one anti-inflammatory subset of those macrophages, two

587
00:34:36.988 --> 00:34:40.948
of them seem to be the most different in terms

588
00:34:41.028 --> 00:34:44.089
of transcriptional changes between the wild type and the knockout,

589
00:34:44.569 --> 00:34:47.947
suggesting a possible role for GPNMB on

590
00:34:48.129 --> 00:34:49.208
neighboring cells.

591
00:34:51.208 --> 00:34:55.069
So these two subtypes of macrophages we saw as being the

592
00:34:55.149 --> 00:34:55.528
most

593
00:34:57.488 --> 00:35:01.448
changed by the knockout in terms of the number of differentially expressed

594
00:35:01.528 --> 00:35:05.408
genes, express C1Q genes and SPP1

595
00:35:05.448 --> 00:35:09.308
gene respectively, and both of them, upon the

596
00:35:09.368 --> 00:35:12.088
GPNMB knockout, upregulated many

597
00:35:12.148 --> 00:35:15.868
interferon-induced genes and downregulated

598
00:35:15.948 --> 00:35:17.468
several lipid genes.

599
00:35:18.828 --> 00:35:22.548
We wanted to test whether these genes we saw as

600
00:35:22.888 --> 00:35:26.768
being upregulated in the knockout have any

601
00:35:26.848 --> 00:35:30.468
predictive value in human data. So we created a gene

602
00:35:30.628 --> 00:35:34.328
score using those genes here and saw that

603
00:35:34.408 --> 00:35:38.178
this gene signature was increased in inflamed

604
00:35:38.188 --> 00:35:40.467
tumors from breast cancer patients.

605
00:35:42.508 --> 00:35:46.308
So because we saw all these lipid genes downregulated in the

606
00:35:46.328 --> 00:35:49.508
knockout, we wanted to test this in another way.

607
00:35:49.668 --> 00:35:53.458
So we looked at fatty acid uptake in vivo by those

608
00:35:53.468 --> 00:35:57.198
tumor macrophages and saw that both pro and

609
00:35:57.268 --> 00:35:59.468
anti-inflammatory subsets

610
00:36:00.568 --> 00:36:04.488
from the tumors grown in the knockout mice showed decreased fatty

611
00:36:04.568 --> 00:36:08.498
acid uptake. So literature is suggesting

612
00:36:08.498 --> 00:36:11.848
that lipid-loaded macrophages have anti-inflammatory

613
00:36:11.948 --> 00:36:14.448
properties in multiple disease models.

614
00:36:15.168 --> 00:36:19.028
So this result is consistent with the idea that the GPNMB knockout is

615
00:36:19.148 --> 00:36:22.868
able to shift the phenotype of the macrophages from an

616
00:36:22.948 --> 00:36:26.148
anti to a pro-inflammatory type.

617
00:36:27.288 --> 00:36:31.168
We also tested the ability of macrophages isolated

618
00:36:31.248 --> 00:36:35.168
from tumors to suppress in vitro activated CD8 positive

619
00:36:35.248 --> 00:36:38.688
T cells and saw that the knockout macrophages suppress

620
00:36:38.928 --> 00:36:39.268
them

621
00:36:40.308 --> 00:36:43.426
less.Um, measured by increased

622
00:36:43.496 --> 00:36:47.476
proliferation in the T cells, as well as increased frequencies

623
00:36:47.556 --> 00:36:51.216
of CD8 T cells secreting interferon gamma, TNF

624
00:36:51.236 --> 00:36:52.836
alpha, and granzyme B.

625
00:36:54.596 --> 00:36:58.516
Since our data indicate that the knockout affects

626
00:36:58.596 --> 00:37:02.316
both macrophages and T cells, and that these two cell

627
00:37:02.376 --> 00:37:06.036
types seem to be involved in some sort of crosstalk, we

628
00:37:06.136 --> 00:37:10.016
wanted to see whether the tumor control in the knockout

629
00:37:10.136 --> 00:37:10.376
is

630
00:37:11.336 --> 00:37:14.576
dependent on T cells. So we

631
00:37:15.516 --> 00:37:19.256
saw that when depleting all T cells using an anti-Thy1

632
00:37:19.316 --> 00:37:22.756
antibody, the tumor control from the knockout was

633
00:37:22.796 --> 00:37:26.636
completely lost. While when only depleting CD8 T

634
00:37:26.676 --> 00:37:30.576
cells, or when we only blocked interferon gamma, the

635
00:37:30.656 --> 00:37:33.776
tumor control was only partially lost.

636
00:37:35.436 --> 00:37:39.176
Also, in tumors, the increase we were

637
00:37:39.256 --> 00:37:42.576
seeing at baseline in the knockout in the pro-inflammatory

638
00:37:42.656 --> 00:37:46.056
macrophages was completely eliminated when we

639
00:37:46.476 --> 00:37:48.236
depleted CD8 T cells.

640
00:37:49.096 --> 00:37:52.576
This arguing that absence of GPNMB

641
00:37:52.856 --> 00:37:56.196
is enabling the CD8 T cells to maybe push the

642
00:37:56.236 --> 00:37:57.716
macrophage phenotype.

643
00:37:59.896 --> 00:38:00.096
So,

644
00:38:00.976 --> 00:38:04.596
due to all these changes in the immune compartment we were seeing, we

645
00:38:04.656 --> 00:38:08.176
wondered whether a knockout of this gene in the

646
00:38:08.196 --> 00:38:11.496
hematopoietic compartment only would lead to tumor

647
00:38:11.576 --> 00:38:15.236
control. And to do this, we made

648
00:38:15.276 --> 00:38:18.786
GPNMB floxed mice that we crossed with the Vav1 Cre mice,

649
00:38:19.396 --> 00:38:23.036
and unexpectedly we saw that there was no tumor control

650
00:38:23.836 --> 00:38:26.096
in either of the models that we were using.

651
00:38:27.216 --> 00:38:30.976
To look at the hematopoietic compartment in a different way, and

652
00:38:31.036 --> 00:38:34.996
also be able to distinguish the non-immune compartment from the

653
00:38:35.076 --> 00:38:39.016
immune compartment, we made bone marrow chimeras in which

654
00:38:39.096 --> 00:38:42.816
either the host or the bone marrow had the gene deletion.

655
00:38:43.436 --> 00:38:46.796
And our results show that absence of

656
00:38:46.856 --> 00:38:50.795
GPNMB from the host led to tumor control, while

657
00:38:50.856 --> 00:38:54.556
when GPNMB was absent from the bone marrow, there was no tumor

658
00:38:54.616 --> 00:38:55.216
control.

659
00:38:56.156 --> 00:38:59.916
The tumors grew slightly faster. So our

660
00:38:59.996 --> 00:39:03.576
next hypothesis for this scenario was that either

661
00:39:05.016 --> 00:39:06.796
a non-immune compartment or

662
00:39:07.776 --> 00:39:11.476
macrophages that are non-bone marrow derived, tissue resident,

663
00:39:11.776 --> 00:39:15.376
are targeted by GPNMB and important for tumor

664
00:39:15.476 --> 00:39:15.926
control.

665
00:39:17.076 --> 00:39:20.236
So to test this, we crossed our floxed

666
00:39:20.276 --> 00:39:23.816
mice with the LysM Cre mice

667
00:39:24.356 --> 00:39:27.826
and were able to see that when

668
00:39:27.856 --> 00:39:31.446
GPNMB is absent from cells targeted by the LysM

669
00:39:31.516 --> 00:39:35.356
promoter, we see tumor control. And because the

670
00:39:35.396 --> 00:39:39.245
LysM Cre is known to target some tissue-resident macrophages

671
00:39:39.396 --> 00:39:41.316
while the Vav1 Cre doesn't,

672
00:39:42.356 --> 00:39:46.116
we think that this result is suggesting that GPNMB

673
00:39:48.096 --> 00:39:51.436
knockout is targeting some non-bone marrow derived tissue-resident

674
00:39:51.496 --> 00:39:55.136
macrophages, and this leads to tumor control.

675
00:39:56.396 --> 00:39:59.996
So in conclusion, knockout of host-derived GPNMB

676
00:40:00.076 --> 00:40:03.856
leads to a shift in two anti-inflammatory

677
00:40:03.956 --> 00:40:06.096
subsets of macrophages from tumors,

678
00:40:07.396 --> 00:40:11.276
and knockout of GPNMB in cells targeted by the LysM promoter and not

679
00:40:11.376 --> 00:40:14.656
by the Vav1 promoter is sufficient to enhance tumor control,

680
00:40:15.216 --> 00:40:18.596
suggesting a role for non-bone marrow derived tissue-resident

681
00:40:18.656 --> 00:40:19.456
macrophages.

682
00:40:22.036 --> 00:40:22.435
Thank you.

683
00:40:29.576 --> 00:40:31.076
We have time for a few questions.

